AGI -&nbsp;<span> “Open Heaven!”, Boniface VIII said. And on the heart of men forgiveness came down. It was February 22, 1300 when the pope opened the divine passage and announced in Rome the first Jubilee of the Catholic Church.» </span
<span> On 24 December 2024 the rite repeated again, when Francis opened the Holy Door in the Vatican > wishing the Jubilee year that will end next December. The ancient document established that the period of jubilee indulgence began (retroactively) in Christmas 1299, was valid twelve months and was repeated every one hundred years.> </span>
<span> In the centuries, however, some pontiffs have changed cadence: from 100 to 50, then 33 and finally 25 years > (apart from extraordinary dates). The 1300s event was so new and important that Dante Alighieri also arrived in the Urbe to not miss it. Today the Vatican emphasizes the presence of the famous Florentine: “According to the most widespread literary reconstruction – writes – Dante’s seven-day imaginary journey between </span> </span> </span> </span> Purgatorio</span> </span> </span> </span> </span> </span>, takes place in the year of the first Jubilee, 1300... the path of redemption that the poet imagined. </span
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<span> To give the events the right order you need to take a step back. As from liturgy before Christianity, the Jews also celebrate their Jubilee Year.> The period falls every seven times seven years> and takes its name from the raton horn that announced it – </span>yobel</span><span> – which, in Latin version, stands precisely for “jubilee”. And then, always remaining in the shadow of the cross, there are also other feasts of forgiveness that are still respected today and re-evoke on the day of their birth date. That is, the indulgence of the Porziuncola > (or Assisi, in Umbria, 1-2 August 1216); the Forgiveness of Collemaggio> (Abruzzo, 28-29 August 1294); the great Jubilee (Rome, 1300) initiated by Pope Boniface. </span
<span> Before asking and obtaining the remission of sins, the pontiff established that, including the Vatican, believers should go on pilgrimage to other papal basilicas:> St. Paul Outside the Walls, St. Mary Major and St. John Lateran. And only after the sacrament of Confession >. The proposed itinerary has not changed even for the Jubilee 2025. The purpose was (and is) clear: to reach the goal of spiritual rebirth, one must be aware of his own guilt. It is essential to be aware that you made a mistake when you even imagined that you had committed it, intentionally or without it. In a radio message of 2 October 1946, Pius XII reflected: “Maybe the greatest sin in today’s world is that men have begun to lose the sense of sin.” </span
